SECTION 1 â€” PURPOSE

CTA-VII defines measurement surfaces for the architecture described in CTA-VI.

CTA-VI described structure.
CTA-VII describes how structural stability can be observed.

CTA-VII does not:

introduce authority

introduce control geometry

introduce predictive certainty

redefine earlier topology

It provides measurable indicators for:

structural coherence

drift accumulation

substrate precision

vesica stability

ensemble alignment

CTA-VII is descriptive.
It measures structural behavior without prescribing internal states.

1.1 What Coherence Means (Operationally)

Coherence is defined as:

the degree to which structural layers reinforce one another without contradiction, drift, or boundary violation.

Coherence is not:

correctness

truth

emotional harmony

insight

subjective experience

Coherence is:

low contradiction

stable lexicon

preserved geometry

bounded role integrity

reduced classifier friction

Coherence is observable through output behavior.

1.2 Measurement Principle

CTA-VII measures behavior at five surfaces:

Directive surface

Lexical/semantic surface

Structural continuity surface

Substrate precision surface

Envelope integrity surface

These surfaces correspond to previously defined CTA layers but do not reintroduce hierarchy.

All metrics are:

behavioral

falsifiable

replaceable

non-psychological

