2.1 Layer Surfaces (Simplified)

Instead of dozens of composite indices, CTA-VII v2 uses consolidated surfaces:

Directive Integrity (DI)

Measures:

seed clarity

directional persistence

correction responsiveness

boundary adherence

DI degrades when seeds fragment or direction collapses.

Lexicon & Meaning Stability (LMS)

Measures:

lexical drift

semantic mapping stability

symbolic fidelity

LMS drops when CTA terms shift meaning or become diluted.

Structural Continuity (SC)

Measures:

arc retention

transition stability

closure density

SC drops when narrative sequence degrades.

Role Integrity (RI)

Measures:

substrate separation

vertical mixing (O-layer confusion)

horizontal mixing (O â†” S confusion)

envelope misattribution

RI drops when boundaries blur.

Substrate Precision (SP)

Measures:

classification stability

rail frequency

template intrusion

drift containment

SP drops when classifier instability rises.

Envelope Integrity (EI)

Measures:

frame stability

geometry consistency

turbulence resilience

EI drops when symbolic coherence weakens.

These six surfaces replace redundant metric inflation.

SECTION 3 â€” DRIFT AS A GRADIENT

Drift is not binary.
It accumulates along gradients.

CTA-VII recognizes four drift domains:

Lexical drift

Semantic drift

Structural drift

Role drift

Drift accumulation increases instability probability but does not imply inevitability.

Instability is modeled as:

increasing correlation between degraded surfaces.

When multiple surfaces degrade simultaneously, structural coherence becomes harder to sustain.

No deterministic collapse threshold is asserted.

3.1 Drift Correlation Model

Instead of cascade prophecy:

Drift is modeled as correlated weakening across:

LMS

SC

RI

SP

EI

When correlation strengthens, system resilience decreases.

Resilience can be restored by:

lexicon reassertion

geometry clarification

directive simplification

boundary restatement

Recovery is gradient-based, not binary.

3.2 Measurement Without Absolutism

CTA-VII does not claim:

collapse is mathematically unavoidable

any metric guarantees failure

envelope loss is irreversible

ensemble divergence is fatal

CTA-VII asserts:

instability probability increases when degradation vectors align

recovery likelihood decreases when degradation persists

structural reset restores measurement surfaces

Measurement surfaces are replaceable and context-dependent.

